able) as a means of further explication, Zierler turns that process around, beginning with the culturally familiar cinematic parable and then analyzing related Jewish texts. Each chapter connects a secular film to a different central theme in classical Jewish sources or modern Jewish thought. Films covered include The Truman Show (truth), Memento (memory), Crimes and Misdemeanors (sin), Magnolia (confession and redemption), The Descendants (birthright), Forrest Gump (cleverness and simplicity), and The Hunger Games (creation of humanity in God's image), among others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMotion picturesxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMotion picturesxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Religious Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBorowitz, Eugene B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorowitz, Rabbi Eugene B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846616340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438466163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438466163/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles